== Couscous ==

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Halve and peel @shallot{1}; mince one half and thinly slice the other. If necessary, cut @broccoli florets{8%oz} into 1-inch pieces.

Melt half the @garlic herb butter{2%tbsp} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add minced shallot and cook, stirring, until just softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in 3/4 cup water, half the @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil. Once boiling, add @couscous{1/2%cup}, cover, and remove pot from heat. Keep covered until ready to serve.

== Roasted Broccoli ==

Toss broccoli on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @vegetable oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast until browned and tender, ~{10-15%minutes}.

== Pork Chops ==

Meanwhile, pat @pork chops{12%oz} dry with #paper towels{}; prick all over with a #fork{} or #knife{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side. Turn off heat; remove from pan and set aside, covered.

Heat another drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in same pan over medium heat. Add sliced shallot and cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add @balsamic vinegar{5%tsp} and simmer until slightly reduced, ~{30%seconds} to 1 minute. Add @cherry jam{2%tbsp}, 1/3 cup water, and remaining stock concentrate. Cook until thickened, ~{3-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and up to @sugar{1/2%tsp}. Turn off heat. Stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Return pork to pan; turn to coat in sauce.

== Serving ==

Fluff couscous with a fork; stir in remaining garlic herb butter. Divide couscous, broccoli, and pork between plates. Top pork with any remaining sauce.

> Part sweet, part tangy, and all-around delicious—that's the thick and super flavorful glaze
> you have in store for you tonight drizzled over these pork chops. The cherry and balsamic
> flavors balance each other out like yin and yang. So we've kept the sides simple with
> roasted broccoli and potatoes to allow the meat and sauce to shine. And boy, do they
> steal the show.